We can see that there are some values missing in the data set, so we need to delete the incomplete cases:

data[data==""]=NA
data[which(!complete.cases(data)),]
##                 Virus case.fatality.rate average.basic.reproductive.rate
## 2 Anthrax (untreated)                20%                            <NA>
## 8             Cholera              1.63%                            2.13
##   primary.mode.of.transmission
## 2                         <NA>
## 8                         <NA>
data=na.omit(data)
sum(is.na(data))
## [1] 0

We have only factors in our data, so we need to coerce the data into numeric:

data[,2]=as.numeric(sub("%", "", as.character(data[,2])))
data[,2]=data[,2]/100
data[,3]=as.numeric(as.character(data[,3]))
str(data)

Also, there are some outliers in the data, and we may delete them:

dataPro=data[data$average.basic.reproductive.rate<60, ]

Plot the Output

Try to plot the output chart:

p=ggplot(dataPro, aes(x=average.basic.reproductive.rate, y=case.fatality.rate, 
                      colour= primary.mode.of.transmission, label=dataPro$Virus))
p=p+geom_point(size=2)+labs(x="Reproductive Rate", y="Fatality Rate", title="The Microbe Scope")
p=p+geom_text(hjust=-0.1, vjust=0, size=2)
p

We can see that in the original plot, the breaks of x axis are 1, 5, 7, 12 and the breaks of y axis are 0.1, 0.2, 0.5 and 0.8. We can do that in our plot:

data1=dataPro[dataPro$case.fatality.rate<=0.1,]
data2=dataPro[dataPro$case.fatality.rate>=0.1,]
p=ggplot(dataPro, aes(x=average.basic.reproductive.rate, y=case.fatality.rate, 
                      colour= primary.mode.of.transmission, label=dataPro$Virus))
p=p+geom_point(size=2)+labs(x="Reproductive Rate", y="Fatality Rate", title="The Microbe Scope")
p=p+geom_text(hjust=-0.1, vjust=0, size=2)
p=p+scale_x_continuous(limits=c(0, 20), minor_breaks=seq(0, 20, 1), breaks=c(1, 5, 7, 12))
p=p+scale_y_continuous(limits=c(0, 1), minor_breaks=seq(0, 1, 0.1), breaks=c(0.1, 0.2, 0.5, 0.8))
p

In the original plot, the y axis is uneven to avoid overlapping labels in the plot. we may try to do that in seperate plots.

p1=ggplot(data1, aes(x=average.basic.reproductive.rate, y=case.fatality.rate, colour= primary.mode.of.transmission, label=data1$Virus))
p1=p1+geom_point(size=1)+labs(x="Reproductive Rate", y="Fatality Rate", title="The Microbe Scope")
p1=p1+geom_text(hjust=-0.1, vjust=0, size=1)
p1=p1+scale_x_continuous(limits=c(0,20))
#p1=p1+scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1, 5, 7, 12), limits=c(0, 20))

p2=ggplot(data2, aes(x=average.basic.reproductive.rate, y=case.fatality.rate, colour= primary.mode.of.transmission, label=data2$Virus))
p2=p2+geom_point(size=1)+labs(x="Reproductive Rate", y="Fatality Rate", title="The Microbe Scope")
p2=p2+geom_text(hjust=-0.1, vjust=0, size=1)
p2=p2+scale_x_continuous(limits=c(0,20))
#p2=p2+scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1, 5, 7, 12), limits=c(0, 20))
#p2=p2+scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(0.2, 0.5, 0.8))

grid.arrange(p1,p2,nrow=2)
